lacename probably derives from Old English <i>wering</i>, <i>wæring</i> ‘dam’ (a derivative of <i>wer</i>, <i>wær</i> ‘weir’) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. There is also a place called Warrington in Buckinghamshire, but it is unlikely to be the source of the surname."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":41,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Isabel de Warrington was born in 1341, in Whalley, Lancashire, England. She married William de Rixton in 1359, in Warrington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 1397, in Warrington, Lancashire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1341–1397":"1341–1397","1337–1399":"1337–1399","1355–1445":"1355–1445","1366–1397":"1366–1397","1382–1453":"1382–1453","1382–1447":"1382–1447","before 1397":"enne 1397","1341":"1341","1382":"1382","1359":"1359","1447":"1447","1337":"1337","1445":"1445","1366":"1366","1355":"1355","1399":"1399","1453":"1453","1397":"1397","about 1366":"umbes 1366","Whalley, Lancashire, England":"Whalley, Lancashire, England","Rixton, Lancashire, England.":"Rixton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England.":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Trafford Bridge, Plemstall, Cheshire, England":"Plemstall, Cheshire, England","Warrington, Lancashire, England":"Warrington, Lancashire, England","R